    if (!isAudioOpened) {
        if (!openAudio()) {
            // Handle audio opening failure
            return 1;
        }
    }

    // Audio is already opened, continue with your program logic

    // ...

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we introduce a global boolean variable `isAudioOpened` to keep track of the audio status. When you call `Mix_OpenAudio()`, if it succeeds, the `isAudioOpened` variable is set to `true`. In the `main()` function, you can check this variable and open the audio if it hasn't been opened yet before proceeding with your program logic.

Note that this approach assumes that you have control over when and how the audio opening occurs in your program. By using a wrapper function or a global variable, you can ensure that the audio opening is handled appropriately and avoid attempting to open the audio multiple times unnecessarily.
